  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The following תּחת רשׁעים cannot signify: on the place of the evil-doers, i.e., in the place where evil-doers are punished (Hirz., Hahn, and others), for תּחת (תּחתּי) only has this signification with the suff. (vid., on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Habakkuk 3:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); but not otherwise than: in the evil-doers' stead, taking them and treating them as such, as Jer. has correctly translated: quasi impios (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 10:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Jerome, cum interfectis). The place first mentioned afterwards is not exactly the usual place of judgment, but any place whatever where all can see it. There He smites those who hitherto held positions of eminence, as of unimpeachable honour, like the common criminal; ספק, Arab. ṣfq, complodere, and then ictu resonante percutere, as the likewise cognate Arab. sf' signifies first to box the ear (as Arab. sfq  equals  ṣfq), then so to strike that it smacks. As little as לכן, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 34:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", was  equals  לכן אשׁר, just so little is אשׁר על־כּן, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 34:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",  equals  על־כן אשׁר (vid., on the other hand what is said on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 18:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " concerning כּי־על־כּן). Elihu wishes to say that they endure such a destiny of punishment, because they therefore, i.e., in order to suffer such, have turned aside from following after God, and have not thought on all His ways, i.e., guidings, by which He manifested Himself to them: they have thus sought to cause the cry of the poor to come (Jer. well renders: ut pervenire facerent ad eum) before Him (עליו, perhaps with the idea of urging forward  equals  לפניו or בּאזניו), and that He may hear the cry of the lowly (construction exactly like ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Job 33:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), i.e., have sought to bring forth His avenging justice by injustice that cries aloud to heaven. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]